Hello Ken-

I think this is a great idea.

I also noticed a while back that there was not a definitive landing page on
the Internet when someone searched for HyperNEAT. For that reason, I started
this wikipedia page a while back, although I meant to put more time into it
than I ended up doing.

http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/HyperNEAT

I was hoping the cloud would begin adding to it and effectively create
something like what your group created, but it's nice that you have created
a more comprehensive and updated resource.



Cheers,
Jeff Clune

Digital Evolution Lab, Michigan State University

jclune@...




> From: Kenneth Stanley <kstanley@...>
> Reply-To: "neat@yahoogroups.com" <neat@yahoogroups.com>
> Date: Sat, 18 Apr 2009 18:43:41 -0000
> To: "neat@yahoogroups.com" <neat@yahoogroups.com>
> Subject: [neat] New HyperNEAT Users Page
> 
> We just put up a HyperNEAT Users Page:
> 
> http://eplex.cs.ucf.edu/hyperNEATpage/HyperNEAT.html
> 
> We have several reasons for making this page available, some of which may be
> of interest to those in this group.  One reason is to promote the work of
> those outside our own EPlex research group.  There is now a fair amount of
> significant work on HyperNEAT from outside EPlex and it is difficult for
> someone interested in HyperNEAT to find out about it from our own publications
> pages, which only features our own work.  Therefore, the HyperNEAT Users Page
> has a section called, "HyperNEAT Projects and Publications from Outside
> EPlex," which features this outside work.
> 
> If you would like your work featured on this page please let me know and we
> will be happy to link it.  It does not have to be an official publication.
> Software, experiments, or informal documents are also welcome.
> 
> Another reason for the page is to have everything about HyperNEAT available in
> one place.  Before this page, there was no clear destination for people
> searching for "hyperneat" in search engines.  This page will help people find
> what they are looking for in an organized manner.
> 
> Finally, we hope the page makes it easier for newcomers to get started.  It
> has a brief introduction explaining the main concepts at a high level and some
> pictures that give the gist of the approach without having to read a whole
> research article.
> 
> Comments are welcome,
> 
> ken
>
